Children who excel at a specific behavior should receive 4 (the highest rating), whereas most children will be between 3 and 2. Those who are still developing and need a lot of support should receive a rating of 1.

4 = Always on their own (No support needed)

(1) Not able on their own (Requires a lot of support) Ignores irrelevant activity/noise (e.g., crying sibling, TV, outside traffic) when working on an assigned task. Waits turn to speak (e.g., does not interrupt others, does not blurt out answers, thinks before speaking). Completes activities that require multiple steps (e.g., fetching multiple things in home or store/market, setting the table, cleaning a room by putting several things away). Comes up with new ways for solving challenges (e.g., repurposes materials or toys, comes up with a new way to build a tower or fort after it collapses, solves a puzzle in a new way, comes up with a new strategy to complete a chore). Identifies and gathers necessary materials before an activity (e.g., finds appropriate coat, shoes, hat before going outside; gathers lunch box, homework, and backpack before going to school). Finishes an assigned task that is repetitive (e.g., picking up toys, putting away laundry). Completes an assigned task before moving to a next task. Stops an undesirable behavior when asked (e.g., stops fighting with sibling when asked by parent, stops misbehaving in the household). Completes activities that require remembering lengthy instructions (e.g., rules of a game, household chores, cooking recipe). Expresses themselves in a new way when not understood by others (e.g., tries different ways to communicate their needs and wants). Creates a strategy or plan for completing a task (e.g., chore, homework, puzzle). Remains focused and engaged during lengthy adult-led activities (e.g., religious or performance event, family meal time) by listening carefully and contributing when appropriate. Regains focus/focuses again on an assigned task when interrupted (e.g., family member asks an unrelated question or needs brief assistance). Stops playing or doing something fun when asked (e.g., stops playing with friends when parent asks, stops watching TV when parent asks). Communicates in an organized way (e.g., retells the correct sequence of the events, explains how a game works so it is easy to understand). Adjusts when plans/schedules change (e.g., follows along when daily schedule changes, does not complain when unexpected sickness leads to canceling a family vacation). finishes homework on time and not at the last minute). Remains focused and engaged during collaborative child-led activities (e.g., playing with siblings/peers). Ignores a preferred, fun activity (e.g., playing) when asked to complete an assigned task (e.g., cleaning room). Waits for their turn to act (e.g., waits patiently in line at a grocery store or when sharing a toy with sibling). Completes age-appropriate numerical mental calculation (e.g., adds prices of goods, calculates time, how much they are older than someone else). Understands conflicting perspectives/ideas (e.g., acknowledges a different point of view, accepts different ways of doing things, can see a situation from someone else’s perspective). Checks for mistakes before completing a task (e.g., reviews and corrects errors on class assignments). Persists on a difficult cognitive/learning task (e.g., homework) by trying to figure things out, asking questions, and not quitting. Answers questions or tells a story without getting distracted by small details and/or losing train of thought. Stops and thinks before acting (e.g., does not run out in front of a car, does not grab things they shouldn't). Remembers and considers all options when making a choice (e.g., what to do when they get stuck on a household task or face a problem, food options). Connects ideas/experiences to other ideas/experiences (e.g., identifies connections between books/movies and lived experiences, uses strategies learned at school to complete activities at home). Begins plans or routines without prompting (e.g., takes an initiative to help a family member, starts daily household chores on their own). Gets deeply engaged in an activity they choose for themselves (e.g., drawing, reading, cooking, building, sports, games). Remembers physical directions, patterns, and where things are (e.g., knows walking routes, finds things in a grocery store, good at searching for a lost item or playing hide-and-seek). Adapts behavior based on what is required by the situation (e.g., switches characters/roles while playing a game, changes behavior based on playtime or study time). Negotiates and incorporates peers' suggestions without conflict or resistance (e.g., works with others to plan roles during pretend play, negotiates with sibling about how to complete chores together).
